<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Noon EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Sunday, Aug. 15, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Los Angeles Synagogue Vandalized  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Congregants of a Hollywood area temple  
arrived for weekend services to see a swastika and ``Jews die'' 
spray-painted on a wall, just days after a shooting spree at a 
Jewish community center in another part of the city. ``I believe 
it's a copycat thing,'' police Sgt. Sanford Rosenberg said of the 
graffiti discovered yesterday at Temple Knesset Israel. No arrests 
were made. The temple plans to hire a security guard for the holy 
days in September. Police said patrols in the area will be stepped 
up. 

</P>
<P>
	Bush Cements Front-Runner Status  
</P>
<P>
	AMES, Iowa (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush's strong showing in  
the Iowa straw poll places him exactly where most expected: as the 
breakaway leader to take the GOP presidential nomination. Despite 
no Iowa straw poll winner ever going on to win the nomination, Bush 
says he's ``on the road to winning the nomination.'' Steve Forbes 
and Elizabeth Dole finished second and third in yesterday's 
nonbinding poll. Former Tennessee Governor Lamar Alexander is 
almost certain to drop out of the race following his weak showing, 
sources close to his campaign said. 

</P>
<P>
	House-Hunting Clintons Visit N.Y.  
</P>
<P>
	RYE BROOK, N.Y. (AP) -- President Clinton and Hillary Rodham  
Clinton toured a home today in this New York City suburb near the 
Connecticut line during a quick house-hunting trip. The Clintons, 
accompanied by daughter Chelsea and the first lady's mother, 
Dorothy Rodham, are expected to visit several Westchester County 
homes. The first had a low stone wall and a tree-shaded drive. 
Reporters were kept at a distance from the house. Mrs. Clinton, 
considering a run for the U.S. Senate, must move to New York by 
Election Day 2000 to be eligible. 

</P>
<P>
	Ga. Plant Worker Dies of Burns  
</P>
<P>
	SMYRNA, Ga. (AP) -- One of seven workers injured in an explosion  
at a Georgia Power coal-burning plant died of burns early today. 
The victim, who wasn't identified, died between 4 a.m. and 5 a.m., 
said Frankie Smith, a nursing supervisor at Grady Memorial 
Hospital. She said two other patients are in critical condition and 
two in satisfactory condition. The explosion happened yesterday at 
Plant McDonough, northwest of Atlanta, when a chemical that workers 
were using to clean equipment ignited with coal dust. 

</P>
<P>
	Russians, Islamic Militants Clash  
</P>
<P>
	MAKHACHKALA, Russia (AP) -- Russian warplanes and paratroopers  
attacked rebel targets today to try to dislodge Islamic militants 
holding villages in the Caucasus Mountains republic of Dagestan. 
Russia's offensive is concentrated just a few miles from Dagestan's 
rugged border with Chechnya, and the Interior Ministry said it 
bombed guerrilla points just inside Chechnya yesterday. Russian 
officials have threatened the standoff could ignite a wider war. 
The Russian Foreign Ministry, meanwhile, is seeking international 
support for Moscow's actions in Dagestan. 

</P>
<P>
	Iraq Says U.S., Britain Blocking Aid  
</P>
<P>
	BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) -- The Iraqi government has accused the United  
States and Britain of preventing aid from reaching Iraq's children, 
who according to a new UNICEF report, are dying at an alarming 
rate. Iraqi Health Minister Omed Medhat Mubarak told reporters 
yesterday that only 60 percent of medicines ordered by Iraq under a 
U.N. oil-for-food program have arrived in the country. The U.N. 
sanctions, imposed after Iraq's invaded Kuwait in 1990, prevent 
Iraq from selling oil outside the humanitarian program. Iraq has 
been accused of hoarding aid and diverting money to military needs. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. To Aid Nigerian Energy Industry  
</P>
<P>
	ABUJA, Nigeria (AP) -- U.S. Energy Secretary Bill Richardson  
signed a tentative cooperation agreement to aid Nigeria's troubled 
oil industry and other energy sectors in return for substantial 
free market reforms, officials said today. Richardson signed the 
memorandum of understanding with Nigeria's Energy Minister 
yesterday in Nigeria's capital of Abuja. The document calls on 
Nigeria to begin privatizing state energy companies and remove 
investment barriers. In return, the United States will provide 
short-term aid to help alleviate oil, gas and electricity shortages 
in Nigeria. 

</P>
<P>
	Hakkinen Wins Hungarian Grand Prix  
</P>
<P>
	BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) -- Defending Formula One champion Mika  
Hakkinen led from start to finish in his McLaren-Mercedes to 
capture the Hungarian Grand Prix today and gain ground on his 
Ferrari challenger Eddie Irvine. Hakkinen ended Irvine's two-race 
winning streak and moved within two points of the Ferrari driver. 
Irvine slid off the track on lap 63 and lost second place to 
Hakkinen's McLaren-Mercedes teammate David Coulthard. Irvine 
finished third. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
