<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Armed Group Kills 29 in Algeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) -- An armed group killed 29 people in  
southwestern Algeria and injured three others Sunday in the worst 
violence since the country's president took office in April, the 
Algerian security forces said. 
</P>
<P>
	The attack took place near Beni Ounif in western Algeria, close  
to the border with Morocco, the security forces said. Hospital 
sources said the death toll could be as high as 40, but that figure 
could not be independently confirmed. 
</P>
<P>
	No details on the attack were immediately available, and no one  
claimed responsibility for the attack. Such massacres are usually 
blamed on the Armed Islamic Group, which appears to want to 
sabotage the peace efforts of President Abdelaziz Bouteflika. 
</P>
<P>
	The attack comes at a time when Bouteflika is trying to persuade  
Algerians to accept a plan of national reconciliation that includes 
an amnesty for Islamic militants not convicted of murder, rape or 
planting bombs. 
</P>
<P>
	The campaign for the Sept. 16 referendum on national  
reconciliation opens this week, but the renewed violence could 
derail Bouteflika's peace plans. 
</P>
<P>
	Bouteflika is hoping for strong approval of his plan and has  
said he will resign if it doesn't pass. 
</P>
<P>
	Interior Minister Abdelmalek Sella had warned earlier this month  
that Islamic groups would carry out attacks in an effort to derail 
Bouteflika's peace plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Security checks were set up Sunday on roads leading in and out  
of Algiers in an effort to prevent attacks in the Algerian capital. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 100,000 people have been killed in the North  
African country since 1992, when an Islamic insurgency erupted 
after the military-backed government canceled elections the 
now-banned Islamic Salvation Front was poised to win. 
</P>
<P>
	About 60 people have died in attacks since Aug. 1. Several bombs  
have gone off in Algiers, which had been relatively calm in recent 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	Algeria experienced a period of unusual calm following  
Bouteflika's election, but a new wave of violence that erupted in 
midsummer shows little sign of abating. 
</P>
<P>
	False bombs alerts are on the rise, and some journalists have  
received anonymous death notices. No one has claimed responsibility 
for the attacks or threats. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
