<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Thai State-Owned Bank To Get Boost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Thailand's central bank has approved  
the injection of $3 billion (108 billion baht) into state-owned 
Krung Thai Bank, which is saddled with massive non-performing 
loans. 
</P>
<P>
	The program will swap debt for equity in the bank, Thailand's  
second largest commercial bank, and should keep it afloat in the 
short term, Finance Ministry officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Thai banking industry is swamped in non-performing loans  
estimated at nearly half of all lending in the financial system. 
</P>
<P>
	The inability of banks to restructure or otherwise cope with  
such debts is seen as the biggest hurdle to Thailand emerging from 
the two-year-old Asian economic crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Krung Thai and government authorities set up a new  
company to manage the bank's non-performing loans. 
</P>
<P>
	Better loan management and the new injection of funds will help  
Krung Thai for now, Wuthichai Pongprasit, Finance Ministry 
comptroller general, said Friday, but ``in the longer term, it 
depends on the situation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The central bank's rescue fund will carry out the conversion.  
The fund is already the largest creditor of two failed smaller 
banks whose assets were absorbed by Krung Thai under a government 
plan to restructure the financial system. 
</P>
<P>
	At the end of March, non-performing loans of Krung Thai Bank  
stood at about $10 billion, or 58 percent of its outstanding 
credit. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
