<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Iowa Poll a Momentum Boost for Bush </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- A late and reluctant entry in Iowa's  
straw poll, George W. Bush trounced the Republican presidential 
field in an impressive display of organizational strength that will 
serve him deep into the primary season. 
</P>
<P>
	The twice-elected Texas governor, already established as the  
leading money-raiser and the favorite in polls, proved his 
political team can convert his celebrity into actual votes. 
</P>
<P>
	On a sunny Saturday afternoon, 7,418 Iowans boarded buses to  
central Iowa to stand in long lines and cast their nonbinding 
ballots for the son of former President George Bush. He got nearly 
one-third of the vote in a field of nine. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know anybody in positions two through 12 who doesn't  
view George Bush as the front-runner,'' said GOP Gov. John Engler 
of Michigan, who campaigned for Bush in Iowa. ``They're all 
shooting at him, so he has to take on the field and ... he did it 
successfully.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush made his first campaign trip to this initial caucus state  
just two months ago, surprising aides by predicting a big victory 
in the straw poll. Republican leaders in Iowa, including Rep. Greg 
Ganske, had advised Bush to skip the contest -- or at least lower 
expectations -- to avoid an embarrassing defeat. 
</P>
<P>
	But in meetings before that initial June trip, Bush heard from  
leaders of his Iowa team who said he could win -- and big. They said 
the contest would limber up his organization. They also warned that 
bypassing the poll might cause some Iowa supporters to question his 
resolve. 
</P>
<P>
	So Bush jumped into the straw poll contest with two goals: build  
a tidal wave of momentum and winnow the GOP field. 
</P>
<P>
	The early results were promising.  
</P>
<P>
	Former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander, in direct competition  
with Bush for moderate voters, finished sixth and is expected to 
suspend his campaign this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not interested in spending the next six months running  
down George Bush and arguing with the media to take me seriously,'' 
Alexander said on NBC's ``Meet the Press'' on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Dan Quayle, vice president under Bush's father, finished eighth  
-- behind three other social conservatives, including commentator 
Alan Keyes. Quayle pledged Sunday to stay in the race, but it is 
hard to imagine that Quayle could threaten Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	Basking in triumph, Bush said of the field: ``I think  
everybody's going to have to reassess their positions and find out 
whether or not they can stay competitive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some of his rivals fared well.  
</P>
<P>
	Millionaire conservative Steve Forbes drew almost 5,000 voters  
to Ames, Iowa, finishing second to bolster his argument he is the 
only person with the resources to beat Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	Taking third was Elizabeth Dole, former president of the  
American Red Cross -- a finish high enough to claim she is expanding 
the GOP base for young and professional women. The showing keeps 
Dole in the race long enough to make a run at Bush if he falters; 
it also adds to a resume that could land her the No. 2 spot on the 
ticket. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're off to New Hampshire, ladies and gentlemen,'' a bouyant  
Dole told volunteers Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington activist Gary Bauer's fourth-place showing was the  
best performance among social conservatives. ``I am the one true 
conservative candidate,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's political team will not waste a minute to build on their  
momentum. Top strategist Karl Rove flew to South Dakota on Sunday 
to begin organizing for the state's April primary. The rest of 
Bush's crew returned to Austin, Texas, where the fund-raising 
operation already was fielding calls from contributors ready to 
board the Bush bandwagon. 
</P>
<P>
	Having shown they can build a grass-roots operation in Iowa,  
Bush supporters are continuing their work elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was truly a remarkable weekend,'' said Gov. Marc Racicot of  
Montana, who campaigned for Bush. ``Several thousand people came 
from miles around this wonderful state to have a voice in the 
democratic process. And, you know, their voices were heard.'' 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Ron Fournier is the national political writer  
for The Associated Press. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
