<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AirTran, Southwest Raise Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Two low-cost carriers raised their fares over the  
weekend with some tickets out of Atlanta going up by as much as 10 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	AirTran Airlines raised its prices as much as $40 per roundtrip  
on some walk-up and first-class fares. Most seven- to 
14-day-advance-purchase tickets increased about $10 per roundtrip, 
while airfares requiring a three-day advance purchase increased by 
up to $20 per roundtrip. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some markets have seen an increase of 10 percent, while others  
are averaging around 5 percent,'' Tom Parsons, editor of 
Bestfares.com, said Sunday. Parsons tracks airline fares and acts 
as a travel agent through his Internet company. 
</P>
<P>
	Most major airlines quickly matched the increase on routes where  
they compete with AirTran, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dallas-based Southwest Airlines also slightly raised air fares.  
Many routes increased by $1 each way and others increased by $3 
each way. 
</P>
<P>
	``The good news for the traveling public is that when Southwest  
has a fare increase, it is a minor irritation,'' Parsons said. 
</P>
<P>
	Southwest spokeswoman Linda Rutherford said the fare increase  
will not be on every flight, but price hikes will be for both 
advance purchase and walk-up fares. Southwest, the nation's 
fourth-largest carrier in terms of customer boardings, serves more 
than 50 cities in 28 states and is expanding its service into the 
eastern United States. 
</P>
<P>
	A telephone message left with AirTran in Orlando, Fla., was not  
immediately returned. AirTran, formerly known as ValuJet, flies to 
31 cities in the eastern and midwestern United States, including 
Chicago, Houston, Newark, N.J., and Washington, D.C. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
