<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Industry Workers Rally in Hollywood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Thousands of film industry workers rallied in  
Hollywood to support state legislation aimed at preventing the 
flight of film productions to other countries, most notably Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	Pounding drums and hoisting American flags, the protesters  
marched on Sunday down a closed-off stretch of Hollywood Boulevard, 
then listened to speeches by actor Edward James Olmos and other 
industry workers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am saying, bring Hollywood home,'' Olmos said. ``How do we  
do that? We get the best minds we have to tell our politicians that 
our workers be included. Don't leave the United States of 
America.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the state Assembly, two bills have been passed that would  
provide tax credits for certain productions using California labor. 
</P>
<P>
	According to a recent study commissioned by the Screen Actors  
Guild and the Directors Guild of America, 285 of 1,075 
U.S.-developed film and TV productions last year were so-called 
``runaway productions'' for economic reasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Many filmmakers take their projects to other countries to save  
money. In Canada, it can be 25 percent cheaper to make a film. That 
country captured 81 percent of those ``runaway'' productions last 
year, the study said. 
</P>
<P>
	In all, ``runaway'' production has doubled since 1990, the study  
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
