<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gun Show Held at Colorado School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANCOS, Colo. (AP) -- The scheduled return of students to  
Columbine High School today did nothing to lower attendance at a 
gun show held over the weekend at a Colorado high school. 
</P>
<P>
	The head of the Mancos Valley Lions Club Gun and Knife Show said  
negative publicity undoubtedly boosted attendance. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sure we hurt with the people (at Columbine), but we're a long  
way from there,'' said Bill Nittler, chairman of the event. Mancos 
is a town of about 1,000 residents in far southwestern Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	Four months after the massacre at Columbine outside Denver,  
which left 15 people dead, including the two teen-age gunmen, 
hundreds turned out for the two-day show held in the cafeteria of 
Mancos High School. 
</P>
<P>
	Admission was $3 and brought in an estimated $2,000 for the  
Lions Club, which will use the money to help people in need, 
Nittler said. 
</P>
<P>
	Attendees questioned by reporters saw little or no connection  
between Columbine and their annual gun show. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would sit in history class looking out the window and count  
a hundred guns in pickup trucks in the parking lot. Nobody shot 
anybody,'' 36-year-old gun exhibitor Bruce Dominey said, recalling 
his days at Mancos High School. ``Guns aren't the problem. They've 
got it all backwards.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before allowing the show, local school board members took notice  
of complaints by a teacher in nearby Durango who said it was 
inappropriate to hold a gun show in the wake of the Columbine 
massacre. 
</P>
<P>
	But no one raised a protest at a subsequent board meeting to  
reconsider the show's location. 
</P>
<P>
	Tim Ward, 35, the father of four daughters, said he had no  
qualms about having his girls at the show. Asked what his children 
know about guns, he replied, ``They know not to touch them.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
