<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Sunday, Aug. 15, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Europeans, Iranian Kidnapped in Iran  
</P>
<P>
	DUBAI, United Arab Emirates (AP) -- Four Europeans and an Iranian  
were kidnapped in central Iran, the Iranian news agency reports 
today, and a Spanish official says the incident may be related to 
drug trafficking. The four tourists -- three Spaniards and an 
Italian -- and the Iranian were seized last night from a hotel in 
the town of Kerman, 550 miles southeast of Tehran, the Islamic 
Republic News Agency said. Kerman's head of security, Abbas 
Doagooie, told the agency that the kidnappers were being pursued by 
security forces and all exits and entries to the province were 
being monitored. Neither the identity, nor the motive of the 
kidnappers was known, the agency said. The report gave no other 
details. 

</P>
<P>
	Rwandan, Uganda Troops in Fight  
</P>
<P>
	KISANGANI, Congo (AP) -- Rwandan and Ugandan troops sharing  
control of the divided northern Congolese city of Kisangani 
exchanged fire for the first time, their commanders said today. The 
clash brought tensions between the two allies in the yearlong 
rebellion to oust Congolese President Laurent Kabila to a boiling 
point, as a rebel leadership dispute in which they've taken 
opposing sides now threatens to engulf them as well. Rwandan 
commanders said Ugandan soldiers at Kisangani's main airport, 15 
miles east of the city, opened fire late last night on Rwandan 
positions at the airfield in an attempt to dislodge them. But 
Rwandan troops returned fire, wounding several Ugandan soldiers. 

</P>
<P>
	Iowa Test No Problem for Bush  
</P>
<P>
	AMES, Iowa (AP) -- As expected, Texas Governor George W. Bush  
easily won in the Iowa straw poll yesterday, receiving nearly one 
third of the vote. Bush said he's ``on the road to winning the 
nomination.'' Steve Forbes and Elizabeth Dole finished second and 
third in the nonbinding poll. Weak showings by former Vice 
President Dan Quayle and Lamar Alexander staggered their campaigns. 
Alexander, the former Tennessee governor, is almost certain to drop 
out of the race, sources close to his campaign said. Quayle faces 
deep troubles as well. 

</P>
<P>
	Clashes Erupt in Northern Ireland  
</P>
<P>
	LONDONDERRY, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Catholic militants fought  
with police, torched trucks and tossed fire bombs Saturday, 
protesting hard-line Protestant parades across Northern Ireland. 
Scuffles left dozens of officers and demonstrators injured in 
Belfast before culminating in protests in Londonderry, where 
Protestants celebrated the northern city's 1689 defense from a 
besieging Catholic army. Groups traditionally start marching in 
other towns before gathering here for the main parade. Suspected 
Irish Republican Army members hijacked and burned four trucks and 
vans on the city's Catholic west side in Londonderry, while more 
than 10,000 Protestant members of the Apprentice Boys fraternal 
group paraded through the city center nearby. 

</P>
<P>
	Russian Forces Battle Militants  
</P>
<P>
	MAKHACHKALA, Russia (AP) -- Russian forces fought Islamic  
militants in scattered skirmishes in Dagestan Saturday, suffering 
at least four deaths as officials admitted that the rebels remained 
in control of seven villages. The fighting was concentrated in the 
Caucasus region of Dagestan, a mountainous Russian republic that 
borders breakaway Chechnya. A Dagestani government spokesman said 
the heaviest ground fighting was in villages north of the main 
combat zone in Dagestan's Botlikh district. A force consisting 
mostly of local volunteers repelled rebel attacks for three hours, 
killing at least seven militants, the Russian Interior Ministry 
said. 

</P>
<P>
	Pressure To Oust Milosevic Mounts  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- As pressure mounts from within  
Yugoslavia to oust President Slobodan Milosevic, vice premier 
Tomislav Nikolic -- an ultranationalist -- told a German magazine 
that Milosevic should resign ``not because the West demands it, but 
rather because he capitulated in Kosovo.'' On the other end of the 
political spectrum, Serbia's opposition leaders today warned 
Milosevic to resign or face an intense round of fall protests. Most 
Kosovo Serbs feel betrayed by Milosevic, who first provoked NATO's 
bombing campaign by refusing to agree to a Kosovo peace settlement, 
only to agree to terms he originally rejected after the bombing, 
effectively losing control of Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Woods, Weir Lead PGA Championship  
</P>
<P>
	MEDINAH, Ill. (AP) -- Heading into today's final round, Mike Weir  
gets another crack at Tiger Woods in Chicago, this time with the 
final major championship of the 20th century on the line. Woods 
made three straight birdies on the front nine and finished with a 
4-under 68 for a share of the lead, his best position in a major 
championship since his record-breaking victory in the 1997 Masters. 
``I just enjoy being in a position where everyone is trying to beat 
me,'' Woods said. ``If you have a lead, everyone else will have to 
shoot that much better. But that's not the case here.'' 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
  	   	
</P>
