<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Sunday, Aug. 15, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Israel Pushes for Oct. 1 Pullout  
</P>
<P>
	GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip (AP) -- Israel pressed ahead today with  
plans to begin a West Bank pullout on Oct. 1, angering Palestinian 
negotiators who said they were not being consulted. Prime Minister 
Ehud Barak told his Cabinet today that the army will begin 
preparations for a withdrawal next month. The Cabinet statement 
said Barak planned an October withdrawal ``parallel with 
Palestinian fulfillment of commitments.'' The withdrawal is the 
second scheduled under the peace accords brokered by President 
Clinton at Wye River, Md., last year. 

</P>
<P>
	Reynolds' Board Rejects Alcoa Offer  
</P>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Reynolds Metals Co. rejected today a $5.6  
billion takeover bid by Alcoa Inc. as inadequate, a decision likely 
to set off a bidding scramble for the No. 3 aluminum manufacturer. 
Already, a Chicago-based investment firm, Michigan Avenue Partners, 
said it has made a superior all-cash offer for Reynolds though it 
declined to disclose details of the bid. The offer came after 
Pittsburgh-based Alcoa, the world's largest aluminum company, 
disclosed its unsolicited $65 a share cash-and-stock offer on 
Wednesday. 

</P>
<P>
	Yugoslav Accuses Opposition Leaders  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Serbia's prime minister accused  
opposition leaders today of being ``terrorists'' who are planning 
to use violence to oust Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic. The 
remarks by Mirko Marjanovic, the prime minister of Yugoslavia's 
main republic and a close aide to Milosevic, were directed against 
the Alliance for Change, which is leading demonstrations calling 
for Milosevic to step down. 

</P>
<P>
	AirTran, Southwest Raise Prices  
</P>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Two low-cost carriers raised their fares over the  
weekend with some tickets out of Atlanta going up by as much as 10 
percent. AirTran Airlines raised its prices as much as $40 per 
roundtrip on some walk-up and first-class fares. Most seven- to 
14-day-advance-purchase tickets increased about $10 per roundtrip, 
while airfares requiring a three-day advance purchase increased by 
up to $20 per roundtrip. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. To Aid Nigerian Energy Industry  
</P>
<P>
	ABUJA, Nigeria (AP) -- U.S. Energy Secretary Bill Richardson  
signed a tentative cooperation agreement to aid Nigeria's troubled 
oil industry and other energy sectors in return for substantial 
free market reforms, officials said today. Richardson, the most 
senior U.S. official to visit Nigeria since an elected government 
was inaugurated nearly three months ago, signed the memorandum of 
understanding with Nigeria's Energy Minister Bola Ige yesterday in 
Nigeria's capital of Abuja. 

</P>
<P>
	Rwandan, Ugandan Troops Clash  
</P>
<P>
	KISANGANI, Congo (AP) -- A simmering feud between Uganda and  
Rwanda over how to end a yearlong rebellion in Congo erupted today 
with troops from both sides battling for control of this northern 
city on the Congo River. A sporadic exchange of mortar and gunfire 
that began at the airport outside Kisangani yesterday spread to the 
city center late today. 

</P>
<P>
	Iraq: U.S., Britain Blocking Aid  
</P>
<P>
	BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) -- The Iraqi government has accused the United  
States and Britain of preventing aid from reaching Iraq's children 
-- who are dying at an alarming rate, according to a new UNICEF 
report. Iraqi Health Minister Omed Medhat Mubarak told reporters 
yesterday that only 60 percent of medicines ordered by Iraq under a 
U.N. oil-for-food program have arrived in the country. 

</P>
<P>
	Amtrak Train Smashes Car, Kills 3  
</P>
<P>
	VANCE, Ala. (AP) -- An Amtrak train smashed into a car today  
killing three people in the car. The passenger train carrying 161 
passengers plowed into the car, which had failed to stop at the 
crossing, authorities said. Investigators said the train was 
traveling from New Orleans to New York City about 75 mph. 

</P>
<P>
	`Sixth Sense' Tops Box Office  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- ``The Sixth Sense'' took in $26.1 million  
over the weekend to remain the nation's top movie for the second 
week, while the Steve Martin-Eddie Murphy comedy ``Bowfinger'' 
bowed in at No. 2 with $18.2 million in its first weekend, 
according to estimates. ``The Blair Witch Project'' slipped from 
second to third place with $15.3 million, according to Exhibitor 
Relations Co. Inc. 

</P>
<P>
	Tiger Woods Wins PGA Championship  
</P>
<P>
	MEDINAH, Ill. (AP) -- Tiger Woods is a major champion once again,  
only this time no one is ready to concede him the future of golf. 
With 19-year-old Sergio Garcia putting on the heat with a stunning 
array of shots, Woods gathered himself in time to make a crucial 
par save on the 17th hole and win the PGA Championship by one 
stroke. Woods tapped in for par on the 18th for an even-par 72, 
mustered up enough strength to pump his fist and breathed a huge 
sigh of relief. 

</P>
