<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Roseanne Angry With 1 a.m. Slot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- If Roseanne becomes the new queen of late-night  
television this fall, it won't be by choice. Not by a long shot. 
</P>
<P>
	Her struggling daytime talk show has been assigned by several TV  
stations to start when most of the intended audience is asleep: 1 
a.m. in Phoenix, midnight in Denver, 1:05 a.m. in Minneapolis, 
after an informercial. 
</P>
<P>
	Other stations have dumped Roseanne completely.  
</P>
<P>
	Entering its second year, ``The Roseanne Show'' is not quite  
dead, but not really alive, either. Its star, the former 
blue-collar heroine of situation comedy, is enmeshed in a nasty 
corporate battle. 
</P>
<P>
	She's not talking, but her executive producer, Jeff Wald, is  
tossing a few grenades. He said the show's recent cancellation by 
11 NBC-owned stations was an attempt to strong-arm Roseanne into 
quitting. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't like bullies,'' Wald said, ``and I think they're  
trying to bully her.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't supposed to be this way, of course. It never is. There  
was such enthusiasm when Roseanne agreed to a talk show that 
stations representing 86 percent of the country signed up, even 
though the syndicator, King World, required two-year contracts at 
stiff prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics immediately noticed the show's schizophrenic nature.  
Some days Roseanne wanted to entertain you, other days enlighten 
you. Some days she wanted to make you mad, other days she did so 
unintentionally. It was never clear what ``The Roseanne Show'' was 
really all about. 
</P>
<P>
	In a business where first impressions are crucial, initial  
ratings were lackluster, and they got worse as the year went on. 
</P>
<P>
	``The program itself is getting better,'' said Cindy Velazquez,  
general manager of the ABC affiliate KMGH-TV in Denver. ``It has 
settled into a direction that it didn't have initially. Personally, 
I felt it was all over the map when it first started.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the improvement, ``The Roseanne Show'' was shunted to  
late-night when KMGH made room for its expanded evening news. 
</P>
<P>
	Typically, stations don't have to worry about where to schedule  
shows that do poorly in the ratings. They simply go away, said 
Richard Kurlander, an expert on the syndication market for the 
advertising buying firm Petry Television. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the first time there's been a failure, and the  
syndicator is holding people to their contracts and producing the 
show,'' he said. ``This is new ground.'' 
</P>
<P>
	King World is guaranteed a profit no matter how many people  
watch the show, because of the two-year contract, Kurlander said. 
The decision to continue production is not necessarily obvious; 
King World must worry about alienating stations by holding them to 
a contract that hasn't work out. For now, King World is taking the 
money. 
</P>
<P>
	The only way out for stations unhappy with their contracts is if  
Roseanne walks away. They would get a refund for the second year. 
</P>
<P>
	That's why Wald is convinced NBC executive Pat Wallace is trying  
to push Roseanne out. Wallace ordered ``The Roseanne Show'' taken 
off the air at the NBC-owned stations, a huge blow since it 
includes big markets like New York, Los Angeles and Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they want to change time slots, that's one thing,'' Wald  
said. ``But their avowed interest is to get her to quit. I've never 
heard anything like that in my 35 years in the business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There's more corporate intrigue. King World, after years of  
independence, was bought out by CBS earlier this year, and Wald 
believes NBC hates the idea of paying CBS. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC denies trying to force Roseanne out. It said its stations  
were trying to find a scheduling formula that worked before cutting 
the show out of the fall schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	``We made the decision in an attempt to improve our ratings  
performance,'' Wallace, president of the NBC television stations, 
said. ``The program had not only not lived up to expectations, the 
ratings performance was extremely disappointing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It makes no sense, Wallace said, for NBC to retaliate because of  
the CBS purchase. The network still has to do other business with 
King World, the syndicator of ``Oprah'' and ``Jeopardy.'' Kurlander 
also downplayed this theory, noting that it's CBS -- not NBC -- 
making money as the situation stands. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Roseanne Show'' will be seen in 60 percent of the country  
this fall, instead of 86 percent. King World won't say how many of 
the remaining stations have scheduled it for the graveyard shift; 
Kurlander estimates it's about one-third. Even Wald concedes this 
makes it more difficult to persuade stars to come on the show as 
guests. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't feel good to be taking on somebody this size,''  
Wald said. ``But, by the same token, David took on Goliath, and 
we're not afraid. We're not going to quit. We're going to stay 
there, and whatever stations are running us are going to get the 
best we have to offer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There's at least one clear lesson to be learned: ``We're  
advising stations to be very cautious about any two-year deals,'' 
Kurlander said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
