<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Diamondbacks' Lee Hurt in Practice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Arizona first baseman Travis Lee sprained his  
left ankle while fielding balls in the outfield during batting 
practice Sunday night and said he expects to be sidelined for three 
to five weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Diamondbacks said Lee sustained a moderate sprain. X-rays  
showed no broken bone. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee, in his second major league season, had lost his starting  
job because he was mired in a 2-for-43 slump going into Sunday's 
game against Milwaukee. He was on crutches in the clubhouse after 
the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``When it rains, it pours,'' Lee said. ``This is kind of  
brutal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lee is batting .236 with nine home runs and 50 RBIs.  
</P>
<P>
	Lee had been working out in the outfield in recent days because  
Buck Showalter was considering playing him some there. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee said he was working on gauging the distance of fly balls off  
the bat when he rolled his ankle while planting his foot. He said 
he had turned the ankle several times in the past, but never this 
seriously. 
</P>
<P>
	He fell to the ground in obvious pain as Showalter rushed to him  
and called for the medical cart to take him off the field. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee was considered a cornerstone of the young franchise after  
signing a $10 million signing bonus in 1996. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
