<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US To Aid Nigerian Energy Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ABUJA, Nigeria (AP) -- U.S. Energy Secretary Bill Richardson  
signed a tentative cooperation agreement to aid Nigeria's troubled 
oil industry and other energy sectors in return for substantial 
free market reforms, officials said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson, the most senior U.S. official to visit Nigeria since  
an elected government was inaugurated nearly three months ago, 
signed the memorandum of understanding with Nigeria's Energy 
Minister Bola Ige on Saturday in Nigeria's capital of Abuja. 
</P>
<P>
	The document calls on Nigeria to begin privatizing state energy  
companies and remove trade and investment barriers. In return, the 
United States will provide short-term aid to help alleviate oil, 
gas and electricity shortages in Nigeria. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the West African country is the world's sixth largest  
oil exporter and the fifth largest to the United States, Nigeria 
has for years been hobbled by official mismanagement, violent 
public protests, armed hijackings and kidnappings. Serious fuel 
shortages are common and gasoline is frequently sold only on the 
black market. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, a joint venture between Texaco Inc. and Chevron Corp.  
was forced to stop pumping oil off the coast of Nigeria because 
angry residents in the area blocked supplies from reaching the 
company's platforms. 
</P>
<P>
	The country's first civilian president in 15 years, Olusegun  
Obasanjo, has promised to fight corruption and focus on resolving 
violent disputes between rival groups vying for state oil revenues. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson declared U.S. support for plans by a consortium led  
by Chevron to build a $400 million pipeline that will ship Nigerian 
gas to neighboring Benin, Ghana and Togo. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Clinton administration feels that Nigeria is one of four  
countries in the world that requires important American attention 
in investment,'' Richardson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nigerian National Petroleum Corporation managing director  
Jackson Gauis-Obaseki said Saturday the government had lost more 
than $1 billion in oil revenue this year as a result of violent 
disruptions to the petroleum industry. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
