<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 5 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Sunday, Aug. 15, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Bush Shines in Iowa Proving Ground  
</P>
<P>
	AMES, Iowa (AP) -- George W. Bush cemented his front-runner  
status last night with a convincing victory in the Iowa straw poll, 
passing an early test of political potency that could unravel other 
Republican presidential campaigns. The Texas governor said he's 
``on the road to winning the nomination.'' Bush received nearly one 
third of the straw poll vote, or 7,418. Steve Forbes and Elizabeth 
Dole finished second and third in the nonbinding poll. Weak 
showings by former Vice President Dan Quayle and Lamar Alexander 
staggered their campaigns. 

</P>
<P>
	Russian Forces Battle Militants  
</P>
<P>
	MAKHACHKALA, Russia (AP) -- Russian forces fought Islamic  
militants in scattered skirmishes in Dagestan Saturday, suffering 
at least four deaths as officials admitted that the rebels remained 
in control of seven villages. The fighting was concentrated in the 
Caucasus region of Dagestan, a mountainous Russian republic that 
borders breakaway Chechnya. A Dagestani government spokesman said 
the heaviest ground fighting was in villages north of the main 
combat zone in Dagestan's Botlikh district. A force consisting 
mostly of local volunteers repelled rebel attacks for three hours, 
killing at least seven militants, the Russian Interior Ministry 
said. 

</P>
<P>
	Report: Protesters Sentenced To Die  
</P>
<P>
	DUBAI, United Arab Emirates (AP) -- Iran's Islamic Revolutionary  
Court reportedly has condemned to death instigators of last month's 
mass protests, Iran's worst unrest since the 1979 Islamic 
revolution. The evening Kayhan daily, which is believed to have 
close ties to Iran's hard-line judiciary, quoted ``informed 
sources'' yesterday, but the story has not been confirmed. The mass 
protests, which highlighted the struggle between reformists and 
conservatives in the government, were sparked by the police's 
storming of a Tehran University dormitory on July 9 after students 
objected to the banning of a reformist newspaper. 

</P>
<P>
	New Computer Is Size of an Aspirin  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The latest from the cyberworld: an  
aspirin-size computer that, embedded in household appliances, could 
let people on the road or at the office use the Internet to cool 
their homes, heat coffee and tape TV shows. Believed to be the 
smallest such computer ever built, the inexpensive device could 
help usher in a new generation of connected home appliances, from 
VCRs to coffee makers to small cameras, controlled over the 
Internet from almost anywhere. 

</P>
<P>
	Report: Only 3 States Y2K Ready  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Only Iowa, Nebraska and North Dakota  
have completely tested their computer systems and are ready to face 
the new year without fear of potentially dangerous Year 2000 
glitches, according to a federal report released yesterday. The 
rest of the states have only 139 days to guarantee reliability of 
their systems that run everything from law enforcement agencies to 
utilities. The report by the General Accounting Office, the 
investigative arm of Congress, was released at a congressional 
subcommittee hearing held in Silicon Valley. 

</P>
<P>
	Opposition To Milosevic Growing  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- In the wake of NATO's bombing  
campaign against Yugoslavia that followed the crackdown in Kosovo, 
sentiment to oust Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic has been 
growing. The newly named vice premier in Yugoslavia -- an 
ultranationalist appointed as part of a government reshuffle meant 
to strengthen Milosevic -- called for the president's resignation. 
On the other end of the political spectrum, Serbia's opposition 
leaders yesterday warned Milosevic to resign or face an intense 
round of fall protests. 

</P>
<P>
	Missing Thailand Protesters Sought  
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Thailand's prime minister has ordered  
the military to find the bodies of 38 people still listed as 
missing after clashes between troops and pro-democracy protesters 
seven years ago. In May 1992, tens of thousands of Thais poured 
into Bangkok's streets to protest an attempt by the military regime 
to stay in power rather than calling promised elections. Troops 
ultimately fired into the crowds, killing at least 50 people, 
wounding 100 and leaving scores missing. 

</P>
<P>
	Woods, Weir Lead PGA Championship  
</P>
<P>
	MEDINAH, Ill. (AP) -- Heading into today's final round, Mike Weir  
gets another crack at Tiger Woods in Chicago, this time with the 
final major championship of the 20th century on the line. Woods 
made three straight birdies on the front nine and finished with a 
4-under 68 for a share of the lead, his best position in a major 
championship since his record-breaking victory in the 1997 Masters. 
``I just enjoy being in a position where everyone is trying to beat 
me,'' Woods said. ``If you have a lead, everyone else will have to 
shoot that much better. But that's not the case here.'' 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
  	   	
</P>
