<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dan Quayle Confident in N.H. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANDOWN, N.H. (AP) -- Former Vice President Dan Quayle reacted  
Sunday to his dismal showing in Iowa straw poll by giving 
confident, emotional speeches punctuated by applause from his 
supporters. 
</P>
<P>
	He alluded to the obstacles he faces, spoke of forging ahead and  
congratulated Texas Gov. George W. Bush for his Saturday victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``As you look at America and the American spirit ... we have  
always been optimistic,'' he said. ``The thing I resent most about 
this administration is the cynicism and distrust they have put out 
into America.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Later, at a picnic in Amherst, Quayle said he wasn't  
disappointed by his eighth-place Iowa showing and will make no 
changes in strategy because of it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I congratulate George Bush,'' Quayle said. ``He won fair and  
square. But you have to win on Election Day. You can buy a straw 
poll. You can't buy an election.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Quayle attributed his finish to spending less money than the  
Texas governor and to a late start in the straw poll campaigning. 
</P>
<P>
	In Sandown and Amherst, Quayle won applause by deriding  
President Clinton, calling for classroom discipline and better pay 
for teachers, and promising to cut taxes 30 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Quayle compared Clinton's administration to the Woodstock music  
festivals in 1969 and this year. Like the first show, Clinton began 
full of youthful ideals, Quayle said. But like this year's 
festival, his administration turned chaotic. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	BEDFORD, N.H. (AP) -- With a swimming pool as a backdrop,  
Elizabeth Dole said Sunday she is diving into the rest of her 
presidential campaign buoyed by the results of the Iowa straw poll. 
</P>
<P>
	Dole, who finished behind Texas Gov. George W. Bush and  
publisher Steve Forbes, called the backyard meeting with several 
hundred supporters a victory party. 
</P>
<P>
	``We came into the top three in a very solid position, without  
spending the millions of dollars spent by the others,'' she said. 
``I think it shows we're bringing in a lot of new people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Stawasz, a former state senator from Hollis, agreed.  
</P>
<P>
	``If you look at the dollars per vote, she got the best mileage  
of anyone in Iowa,'' he said. ``Bush did very well, but what was 
his cost per vote?'' 
</P>
<P>
	As it grew dark, Laurie Doucette of Bedford watched as Dole made  
her way through the crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's as charismatic as ever,'' she said. ``I think it's time  
to see a woman in power. If anyone can do it, she can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dole joked about young girls who approach her saying, ``But I  
wanted to be the first woman president. I tell them, `It will be a 
lot easier for you if I pave the way.''' 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) -- After his fourth-place finish in the  
Iowa straw poll, Gary Bauer said Sunday he plans to take on the 
higher ranked candidates one at a time, starting with Steve Forbes. 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer said he has challenged the New Jersey publisher to a  
debate as a way to dispel Forbes' claim that he best represents 
conservative voters. 
</P>
<P>
	``He tries to claim the conservative mantle, and I don't believe  
it is his,'' Bauer said after meeting with supporters in 
Manchester. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Forbes is his current target, Bauer said he's preparing  
to ``zero-in on anyone who's still ahead of me. With each day, the 
field is going to get smaller, and the issues are going to get 
bigger.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer said he wasn't surprised that he finished ahead of other  
conservative candidates such as former Vice President Dan Quayle. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think what it did was confirm for the rest of the political  
world what we already knew -- that I'm going to be a top-tier 
candidate,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ultimately, issues will determine the outcome of the campaign,  
not money.'' Bauer said. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	AMHERST, N.H. (AP) -- Despite his last-place finish in Iowa's  
straw poll, Republican presidential candidate Orrin Hatch said 
Sunday he is pleased he did as well as he did. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just got in the race late,'' Hatch said at a Republican  
picnic. ``Anybody who knows me knows you should never count Orrin 
Hatch out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch said 558 votes is a respectable total after campaigning  
only 12 days. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't place too much credence in (the poll),'' Hatch said.  
``It was clearly a fund-raiser.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
