<CATEGORY> weather </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Thunderstorms moved across the North Central states on Sunday  
with rain and hail, and stormy weather also developed in parts of 
the Southeast. 
</P>
<P>
	The storms and locally heavy rain spread over parts of eastern  
Montana, North Dakota and the northern edge of Minnesota during the 
afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Weather Service posted severe thunderstorm watches  
and warnings for parts of the three states. 
</P>
<P>
	Hail more than an inch in diameter was reported in parts of  
northern Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	Pockets of showers and stormy weather also developed in eastern  
South Dakota and rolled across southern Minnesota and neighboring 
areas of Iowa into Wisconsin. 
</P>
<P>
	From that area of storms, moisture also stretched off the west,  
with showers in parts of Idaho and western Montana, and rain around 
Washington's Puget Sound area. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Southeast, thunderstorms spread across wide areas of  
northern and southern Florida during the afternoon, and extended 
into southern Georgia. 
</P>
<P>
	Storms also developed along the coast of North and South  
Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	The afternoon also brought monsoon rain to the Southwest, with  
isolated showers and a few thunderstorms spreading northward 
through Arizona and New Mexico into sections of Utah and Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, light to moderate showers lingered over New England,  
the remnants of heavy rainfall and thunderstorms that rolled across 
much of the East on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Showers or thundershowers were possible in parts of Oklahoma,  
Texas and Louisiana. 
</P>
<P>
	Along with showers, cool air also moved across parts of the  
Northwest. Temperatures fell to record lows of 32 at Burns, Ore., 
and to 35 at Elko, Nev. 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday's temperatures around the Lower 48 states ranged from the  
low of 32 at Burns, Ore., to a midday reading of 99 at Blythe, 
Calif. The highest midday heat index was 105 at Homestead, Fla. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
