<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley Comments on Bush's Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALEM, N.H. (AP) -- Republican presidential front-runner George  
W. Bush does not have a ``divine right'' to be president no matter 
how much money he's raised, Democratic rival Bill Bradley suggested 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know him. I've never met him. He seems genial. He's  
governor of a big state. He was re-elected. But with all of those 
attributes, if he didn't have $50 million, who knows? I think this 
is a time when it's possible to raise too much money,'' the former 
New Jersey senator said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley was responding to a question about Bush from Dr. David  
Wallace, one of about 100 people who showed up to meet Bradley. 
</P>
<P>
	``How the hell does a guy like this, a rich kid millionaire with  
a very dubious background, present himself as presidential 
material?'' Wallace asked. 
</P>
<P>
	``You mean you don't think there's a divine right to office?''  
Bradley responded. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, Bush received nearly one third of the votes in the  
Iowa straw poll, placing him first in the nonbinding contest 
between GOP hopefuls. He said the victory will propel him on to 
winning the Republican nomination for president. 
</P>
<P>
	In Salem, Bradley struck familiar campaign themes on what he'd  
like his legacy to be if elected president, saying he wants to 
protect the environment, lead a country at peace, be a good steward 
of a good economy, help kids reach their potential and bring racial 
unity. 
</P>
<P>
	He said his main goal is to help people prosper in times of a  
changing economy, changing technology, military threats and new 
immigration patterns. 
</P>
<P>
	``All of these things are happening simultaneously. One of the  
key jobs of the president is to give people a narrative of where 
they fit in in all of this,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Sunday, Bradley told 30 anti-gun activists in Boston he  
wants to ban the sale of cheaply-made guns known as ``Saturday 
night specials.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He told reporters he favors creating a national gun registry  
system similar to the process now used to register cars. 
</P>
<P>
	The former professional basketball player said he also believes  
in banning gun shows that don't perform background checks and that 
it should be a felony crime for gun dealers to sell guns to people 
who turn around and sell the gun to a felon. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley is challenging Vice President Al Gore for the Democratic  
presidential nomination. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
