<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Drought Prompts Stampede to Market / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) -- With water and feed hard to come by in  
many counties, West Virginia farmers are driving their cattle to 
the auction market earlier than usual. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven of the state's 13 cattle option markets, counted together,  
sold up to 300 percent more cattle this July than a year earlier. 
Figures for the other six were not available from the state's 
Department of Agriculture. 
</P>
<P>
	Ron Crihfield, a farmer in Kentuck, Jackson County, sold 23 cows  
and 23 calves last month -- half of his cattle. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't have the water,'' Crihfield said.  
</P>
<P>
	Jackson County farmer James Bostics sold 15 cows, nearly half  
his livestock, to avoid the cost of buying hay. The Department of 
Agriculture estimates the hay crop is down 50 percent this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``In August we continue to see an above-average number of cattle  
moving,'' said department official Dwayne O'Dell. But he said the 
increased sales are not a cause for concern -- ``People are just 
moving livestock earlier. Many would have normally been marketed in 
October.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, O'Dell said state agriculture officials are worried that  
if the drought continues some farmers may sell all their cattle and 
go out of business. 
</P>
<P>
	Livestock ``are selling at a $50 to $100 deficit as compared to  
what they would normally sell for,'' he said. During a normal 
season, a calf, fattened up by grazing, would weigh about 500 
pounds, but is now only 375 to 400 pounds, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hog farmers in eastern West Virginia also may be selling animals  
earlier than usual. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some hogs may have been moved prematurely because of excess  
heat,'' said Agriculture Commissioner Gus Douglass. Heat leads to 
reduced growth, Douglass said, but ``there is sufficient feed for 
them.'' Hogs are not a key market for the state, he added. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SALEM, Ore. (AP) -- Lumber prices hit an all-time high in the  
first six months of 1999, followed by a precipitous decline that 
has the industry struggling to stabilize itself. 
</P>
<P>
	Many mills ran overtime earlier this summer to take advantage of  
a 35 percent price increase in Douglas fir lumber. Retail lumber 
costs soared, sticking homebuilders and buyers with unexpected 
bills. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a remarkable run-up in lumber prices,'' said Ron  
Parker, president of Hampton Affiliates, a lumber manufacturer in 
Portland, Ore. ``The higher lumber prices have been very welcome 
compared to 1998, which was a difficult year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The roller coaster ride follows a slump last year caused by the  
Asian economic slowdown. Some mills went from temporary shutdowns 
in 1998 to running extra days this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Record home construction, a recovering Japanese market and less  
imported wood from Canada helped fuel the increase, said Butch 
Bernhardt Jr., a spokesman for the Portland-based Western Wood 
Products Association, which represents lumber manufacturers in 13 
Western states. 
</P>
<P>
	Early summer temperatures jump-started the summer construction  
season, pushing demand higher. With single-family housing starts at 
a 20-year high and mills at a lower production level, lumber prices 
skyrocketed, Bernhardt said. 
</P>
<P>
	But the market recently caught up with itself. About three weeks  
ago, prices dropped again as supply exceeded demand. The cost of 
1,000 board feet of Douglas fir 2x4s, for example, dropped from 
$505 in July to $405 now. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
