<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gordon, Blundell Come From Behind </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LEXINGTON, Ohio (AP) -- Although Juan Montoya won Sunday's CART  
Miller Lite 200 by charging from eighth to first, bigger moves in 
terms of numbers were made by Greg Moore and Mark Blundell, the two 
drivers on the last row of the starting grid. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore started 25th and finished 11th. Blundell began the race  
26th and ended 13th. 
</P>
<P>
	``I must have gained at least 10 positions during the pit  
stops,'' Moore said. ``It's great to come back from so far and 
score points in a race where there was so little attrition. It's 
unfortunate that we didn't have track position since it's a tough 
circuit to move up from the rear of the grid.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Blundell posted the third-fastest qualifying time, but had to  
start in last place because his car failed to pass technical 
inspection after qualification. It was his second race since 
fracturing a vertebra May 4 in testing at St. Louis and he wasn't 
sure before the race how his neck was going to hold up under the 
demands of the Mid-Ohio Sports Car Course. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a real workout,'' he said. ``This circuit is one of the  
most physically demanding that we race on, and I knew today would 
be a challenge. I have to say I'm pretty exhausted. My neck was a 
lot more tired than it was after the Detroit race'' (last weekend). 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	OHIO DRIVERS DISAPPOINT: The day wasn't so good for two of the  
three drivers on CART's Ohio-based teams. 
</P>
<P>
	Max Papis of Team Rahal started ninth and finished fifth, but  
teammate Bryan Herta, who was second on the starting grid, had an 
engine problem six laps from the end and placed 21st. Tony Kanaan 
of McDonald's Championship Racing, located about a mile from the 
Rahal shop in the Columbus suburb of Hilliard, started fourth and 
finished 23rd. He left with a fuel system problem on the 58th lap. 
</P>
<P>
	``As they say, 'The engine just blowed up,' '' Herta said. ``The  
engine ran fine and then it was dead. I had no warning that it was 
going. That's kind of the way the season has gone for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Herta and team owner Bobby Rahal acknowledged earlier this  
weekend that they may be parting ways at the end of the season 
after four years, and his finish Sunday wasn't one to add to his 
resume if he has to look for another ride at the end of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not exactly sure what the problem is, but we ran out of  
fuel twice,'' Kanaan said. ``The car was working OK. We just had 
some tough luck today and that happens in racing.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	PENSKE PROBLEMS: The struggles continue for Team Penske and Al  
Unser Jr. The team, still with the most victories in CART history 
by far, hasn't won a race since 1997 and will end its relationship 
with Unser at the end of the season, with Gil de Ferran and Moore 
replacing him. 
</P>
<P>
	Unser started his day one lap after the rest of the field and  
finished 25th after going off course in the 55th lap. 
</P>
<P>
	``On the pace lap, I couldn't hear Roger (Penske) or the crew  
even though they could hear me, because we had a problem with the 
radio hookup in my helmet, so I had to come in and change 
helmets,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was running competitively with the top cars and was trying  
to make up time and I got into turn one too deep, lost the front 
end and ended up in the (barrier of) tires,'' Unser said of his day 
ending. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	GORDON SWITCH: Robby Gordon announced that he's buying an Eagle  
997 from Dan Gurney's All American Racers team and will drive it in 
the season's remaining oval events next Sunday at Chicago and Oct. 
31 at Fontana, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	This will be the third chassis Gordon has driven this season. He  
started the year in a Reynard and switched to a Swift after five 
starts. He will continue driving the Swift in the year's other four 
events and will continue running with a Toyota engine. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm doing this not because I'm dissatisfied with Swift, but  
because I think the Eagle will give us a better chance on short 
ovals,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This definitely opens up the door to closer cooperation (with  
Gurney) next year,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	Gordon said Gurney also has loaned him some of All American's  
engineers for next weekend to help with the chassis transition. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	ANDRETTI DRIVES AGAIN: It seems as though you can't keep Mario  
Andretti off the track at Mid-Ohio, even after his retirement in 
1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years ago, he drove the course in a specially equipped  
championship car for an IMAX film. 
</P>
<P>
	This weekend, he was on the track with another former champion,  
Emerson Fittipaldi, to test a racer that will be used in the Cobra 
Challenge, a ``senior tour'' for retired drivers that will be run 
next year on six road courses and is sanctioned by the Sports Car 
Club of America. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
