<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Shooting Unites Religious Groups </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- For nearly a decade, the Episcopal church and  
the Jewish synagogue shared a sanctuary. 
</P>
<P>
	But the two congregations in suburban Granada Hills had little  
in common, different religions worshipping on different days of the 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, last week, a gunman's bullets changed all that: The  
Episcopal Church of Saint Andrew &AMP; Saint Charles and Temple Beth 
Torah became a safe haven for children escaping a shooting rampage 
at a Jewish community center. 
</P>
<P>
	``That man did more to hurt his cause than anything else he  
could have done. He brought us together, binding us forever in this 
community -- Jewish and Christian,'' said Marv Simmons, a parish 
administrator at the church. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly a week after Buford O. Furrow Jr. allegedly fired 70  
bullets in the lobby of the North Valley Jewish Community Center, 
wounding five people, including three children attending a day 
camp, residents in the suburban Los Angeles community say a moment 
of hate has united two distinctly separate religious congregations. 
</P>
<P>
	Furrow, who surrendered to authorities in Las Vegas one day  
after Tuesday's shootings, also is accused of killing a mail 
carrier of Filipino descent, a Catholic whose funeral Mass on 
Saturday was attended by Rabbi Lawrence Goldmark, head of the Board 
of Rabbis of Southern California. Furrow reportedly targeted the 
mail carrier because he was nonwhite and a federal employee. 
</P>
<P>
	``I suspect the Granada Hills community won't ever be quite the  
same,'' said Rabbi E. Robert Kraus, who leads the temple 
congregation. ``We need to take advantage of this feeling of 
cooperation. ...There's always been a spirit of cooperation, but we 
have an opportunity to come together on a much more practical 
level.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The San Fernando Valley -- home to a large share of Los Angeles'  
600,000 Jews -- is dotted with synagogues and churches. It has long 
been a suburban oasis of single family homes and private, religious 
schools. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the community has been touched by tragedy before -- the  
1994 Northridge earthquake claimed dozens of lives and left 
thousands homeless -- it's the first time anyone came remember an 
act of terrorism. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was different. It wasn't an act of nature. This was pure  
evil,'' said Sue Ashbrook, who attends the Episcopal church. ``What 
was he thinking? He'd make it so we didn't like them? If anything, 
he failed. Instead of separating us, he brought us together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As a way of honoring those who came to the rescue of the  
shooting victims, Jewish groups organized a community-wide event 
Sunday dubbed a ``Unity Rally,'' but the harmony was disrupted by 
two raucous hecklers opposed to Gov. Gray Davis' speech advocating 
gun control. 
</P>
<P>
	The two men shouted and booed the Democrat, who last month  
signed laws restricting gun purchases to one per month and 
tightening a ban on assault weapons. He said after the community 
center shooting that he would push additional ``responsible'' 
gun-control measures. 
</P>
<P>
	``The second amendment is just as important,'' Irv Rubin of the  
Jewish Defense League yelled at Davis. Last weekend Rubin and 
thousands of other Aryan opponents successfully blocked a parade in 
the nation's capital by white supremacists, including Aryan Nations 
members. 
</P>
<P>
	The hecklers handed out fliers to crowd members, including one  
woman who tore up the paper and threw it at Rubin's feet. ``Don't 
leave yourself unarmed against those who want to murder you,'' the 
flier read. ``Gun control laws are only observed by decent people 
and haters aren't decent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney General Janet Reno, who has denounced the attack and  
what she called ``our culture of violence,'' also addressed the 
outdoor rally attended by hundreds. Doctors, firefighters and 
police officers covered the lawn at the California State 
University, Northridge, where the crowd gave a standing ovation to 
the family of the slain mail carrier. 
</P>
<P>
	Signs of hatred were not entirely vanquished. Members of Temple  
Knesset Israel learned Saturday when they discovered a swastika and 
the words ``Jews die'' spray-painted on a wall at the entrance to 
their preschool. Police called the crime a ``copycat thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the Hollywood-area temple's mailbox, police found a letter  
that appeared to be anti-British. Temple president Harvey Shield is 
British. Shield said he now plans to hire a security guard for holy 
days in September, and police plan to step up patrols in the Los 
Angeles neighborhood. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the only remaining victim in the hospital was  
upgraded from critical to serious condition this weekend. 
Five-year-old Benjamin Kadish was attending the Jewish day camp 
when he suffered multiple gunshot wounds. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
