<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Veteran N.J. Sports Writer Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J. (AP) -- Joe Calabrese, a sports writer and  
editor in New Jersey for the past 38 years, died Sunday following a 
long illness. He was 59. 
</P>
<P>
	Calabrese spent the past 12 years covering Rutgers athletics for  
The Star-Ledger of Newark. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't think of anyone who didn't like Joe, or enjoyed being  
around him,'' said Kevin Whitmer, an assistant managing editor at 
The Star-Ledger. ``He was a great storyteller and a tremendous 
influence on the lives and careers of so many people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When he took over the Rutgers beat, Calabrese insisted the  
state's largest newspaper provide better coverage of women's 
sports, which at the time was not a popular opinion. 
</P>
<P>
	``One thing about Joe was, he always did the right thing, or  
what he strongly believed was the right thing,'' said Theresa 
Grentz, the women's basketball coach at Illinois whom Calabrese 
covered when she coached the Rutgers women. 
</P>
<P>
	``Covering us was never a gender issue with Joe, he just saw  
student-athletes who played a game and deserved coverage,'' she 
added. ``It was that simple.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After receiving a journalism degree from Rider, Calabrese began  
his career at The Courier-News in Plainfield in 1961. He also 
worked at the Somerset Messenger-Gazette and Trenton Times. In 
1978, he returned to The Courier-News, which had moved to 
Bridgewater, and was eventually named the sports editor. 
</P>
<P>
	``I got to see Joe interact with young sportswriters,'' said Joe  
Bakes, who worked with Calabrese at both The Star-Ledger and The 
Courier-News. ``He was always so supportive. He nurtured a whole 
generation of New Jersey sportswriters and editors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Calabrese is survived by his wife, DonaLee, and two sons, Chris  
and Matthew. 
</P>
<P>
	Funeral arrangements, which are being handled by the Branchburg  
Funeral Home, were expected to be finalized Monday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
