<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmaker Heads to His Stables </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEVEN VALLEYS, Pa. (AP) -- William Goodling can't get a moment's  
peace in his congressional office, what with telephone calls to 
return, hearings to oversee and votes to cast. 
</P>
<P>
	But minutes after the final gavel drops each week, the chairman  
of the House Education and Workforce Committee rushes home for some 
peace and quiet with the uncomplaining company of five stout mares 
and two offspring. 
</P>
<P>
	There are no beepers, no buzzers and no pink cards in his pocket  
telling the Pennsylvania Republican where he ought to be each 
minute of the day. Away from the madhouse of Capitol Hill, Goodling 
finds therapeutic relief in the stables 90 miles west of 
Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the sun goes down, I enjoy dunging out the stalls,''  
Goodling said recently after feeding his horses, capping a week 
dominated by talk of tax cuts. ``Nobody bothers me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Raising horses for racing is far from a lucrative business.  
Goodling said he barely breaks even after factoring in food, 
medical care and breeding services. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet he enjoys taking care of his horses and tracking the  
offspring he sells. Occasionally, one of them wins a low-profile 
race in Pennsylvania or Delaware. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you only have five mares they become part of the  
family,'' he said. ``I have to follow them all the time. ... I look 
in the papers. I probably generally go to the editorial page first 
and then go to the sports page.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Back at his home and farm in Seven Valleys two hours after the  
last House vote, Goodling wet down two mares, a colt and a filly to 
keep them cool, then brought them into the stables to spray fly 
repellent and offer a feed mix of grain and molasses. 
</P>
<P>
	He then drove to nearby Jacobus to care for three other mares  
there, including one just injured from a brush with a fence. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a twice-daily routine when the 13-term lawmaker is not in  
Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	``My wife does it when I'm not here,'' he said. ``When we go  
away, we have to get my niece in. My niece is a very active 
horsewoman.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Goodling grew up with horses. His father owned one to help out  
with plowing and cultivating the family fruit farm. He got one for 
riding when he returned from Army service in 1948. In the 
mid-1980s, he bought his first horse for breeding -- one that was 
retiring from the racing circuit. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I came back from the service, unlike most people I wanted  
a horse rather than a car,'' he said. ``I'm a horse lover. It's a 
hobby for now, though if I'm ever successful it becomes a 
business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Goodling occasionally learns of tax and other issues affecting  
the thoroughbred industry, but he said he leaves the lobbying to 
others. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides owning the five mares and their offspring, Goodling has  
partial stakes in a pair of studs for breeding. He reported income 
of up to $50,000 from his horse operation last year, but those 
earnings are canceled out by expenses. 
</P>
<P>
	``They eat like horses,'' Goodling said. ``I'm closer to  
breaking even, but again that doesn't count the therapeutic value 
of my involvement. That can be worth a lot.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
